AllLife Credit Card Customer Segmentation¶

Objective: To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.¶

Data Description:¶

  • Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

git repo: https://github.com/GreatLearningAIML1/gl-pgp-aiml-uta-intl-may20-bunty-sunbird/tree/master/project/AllBankCustomerSegmentation

def box_independent_hue(independent):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))
    sns.boxplot(data=df, x = 'Target', y = independent);
    plt.show()

def box_independent(independent):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))
    sns.boxplot(data=df, x = independent);
    plt.show()
    
def dist_plot(independent, skip_dist_plot=False):
    if skip_dist_plot:
        return
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))
    sns.distplot(df[independent]);

def dist_plot_hue(independent):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))
    # sns.countplot(x=independent, hue='Target', data=df);
    plt.hist(df[independent], density=True)
    
def density_plot(independent, dependent):
    sns.distplot(df[df[dependent]=='no'][independent],color='r',label=0)
    sns.distplot(df[df[dependent]=='yes'][independent],color='g',label=1)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
def univariant_contineous(independent, dependent, skip_dist_plot=False):
    # density_plot(independent, dependent)
    box_independent(independent)
    # box_independent_hue(independent)
    dist_plot_hue(independent)
    dist_plot(independent, skip_dist_plot)

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn import metrics

# Variables are mow scaled. Let us now try to create clusters

cluster_range = range(2,15)
cluster_errors = []
silhouette_scores = []

for num_clusters in cluster_range:
    clusters = KMeans(num_clusters, n_init = 5)
    clusters.fit(df_z)
    labels = clusters.labels_
    centroids = clusters.cluster_centers_
    cluster_errors.append(clusters.inertia_)
    silhouette_scores.append( metrics.silhouette_score(df_z, labels, metric = 'euclidean') )

clusters_df = pd.DataFrame({"num_clusters": cluster_range, "cluster_errors": cluster_errors, 
                           "silhouette_scores": silhouette_scores})

# Observation

# to rule out any dilemma between 3, 4 or 5 clusters, we took extra help from silhouette scores. As can be seen that 
# silhouette scores is the highest on 3 and therefore it seems to be a good choice for number of customer segments.

# 3 segments seems to provide highest silhouette score and the elbow diagram shows conversion start at 3 clusters. 
# But, even from 3 to 4, it converged a bit with the 2nd best silhoutte score. It may be worth getting the clusters
# at 4 as well and therefore the next best 'k' value is 4. 3 segments is a good choice since it converged very less 
# after 3 segments and silhouette score is also high at 3
In [39]:
def kmeans_analysis(k):
    
    if 'group' in df.columns:
        df.drop(['group'], axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    if 'group' in df_z.columns:
        df_z.drop(['group'], axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # We could see the bend at 'k', so let us create 4 custers
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, n_init = 5, random_state=12345)
    model = kmeans.fit(df_z)
    
    # Check the number of data in each cluster
    labels = kmeans.labels_
    counts = np.bincount(labels[labels>=0])
    print("Customer count per group: ", counts)
    print()
    
    # print (labels)
    
    # Distribution looks fine.

    # let us check the centers in each group
    centroids = kmeans.cluster_centers_
    centroid_df = pd.DataFrame(centroids, columns = list(df_z) )
    # print(centroid_df.transpose())
    # display(centroid_df.transpose())
    # print()
    
    # silhouette score for 4 segments
    
    print ("silhouette score: ", metrics.silhouette_score(df_z, labels, metric = 'euclidean'))

    # Add cluster number to original data

    predictions = kmeans.predict(df_z)
    predictions
    df["group"] = predictions
    df['group'] = df['group'].astype('category')
    # df.dtypes
    # print(df.head())
    
    custDataClust = df.groupby(['group'])
    display("Mean of feature per group: ", custDataClust.mean())
    # print(custDataClust.mean())

    display("Cluster centroids: ", centroid_df)
    print()
    
    # Visualize the centers
    
    df_z["group"] = predictions
    df_z.boxplot(by = 'group',  layout=(3,4), figsize=(15, 10))
    

    # plt.scatter(df_z[:, 0], df_z[:, 1], c=labels, cmap='rainbow')

# Observation with 5 segments

# Group 4 are the customers with highest Average Credit Limit, have more credit cards and visit online more than 
#         customers from other group. These kind of customers are lowest in count i.e. 50

# Group 1 have most (219) customer count. These are customers that have low average credit limit, less credit cards, 
#          makes less bank visits, average online visits and had to be made more phone calls

# Group 0 have 107 customers. These are customers with average credit limit, good number of credit cards
#         than other groups but group 4, make more bank visits than other groups and low online visits
#         and less number of calls made

# Group 2 have 130 customers. These are customers with average credit limit, good number of credit cards
#         than other groups but group 4 and 0, make fewer bank visits than group 0 and 3 and low online visits
#         and less number of calls made

# Group 3 have 143 customer count. These are customers that have low average credit limit, second lowest credit cards 
#         (more than group 1), makes few bank visits, low online visits and had to be made less phone calls

# With 5 clusters/segments, it can be observed that there are many overlapping/similar boxes. For example, for

from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering 

from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import cophenet, dendrogram, linkage

from scipy.spatial.distance import pdist  #Pairwise distribution between data points

from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import fcluster



    













In [50]:



    


def hierarchical_analysis(method):
    # cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram
    # closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering

    # clean the previously collected grouping information
    cleanup()

    # run the model and collect the cophenet index and distance
    Z = linkage(df_z, metric='euclidean', method=method)
    c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(df_z))

    print ("Cophenet score: ", c)
    
    # Plot the dendogram
    plt.figure(figsize=(25, 10))
    dendrogram(Z)
    plt.show()
    
    # Hint: Use truncate_mode='lastp' attribute in dendrogram function to arrive at dendrogram
    dendrogram(
        Z,
        truncate_mode='lastp',  # show only the last p merged clusters
        p=6,  # show only the last p merged clusters
    )
    plt.show()
    
    return Z

def hierarchical_cluster_analysis(Z, max_d, n_clusters):
    
    # Create clusters at the given distance in dendogram
    clusters = fcluster(Z, max_d, criterion='distance')
    # print (clusters)
    
    print("Silhoutte: ", metrics.silhouette_score(df_z , clusters, metric='euclidean'))
    
    # update the data to have group information
    df_z['group'] = clusters
    df['group'] = clusters
    # display(df_z.head(10))
    # display(df.head(10))
    
    # display mean and count per group
    custDataClust = df.groupby(['group'])
    display("Mean feature per group: ", custDataClust.mean())
    display("Customer count per group: ", custDataClust.count())

    # Hint: Use truncate_mode='lastp' attribute in dendrogram function to arrive at dendrogram
    dendrogram(
        Z,
        truncate_mode='lastp',  # show only the last p merged clusters
        p=n_clusters,  # show only the last p merged clusters
    )
    plt.show()
    
    # plot the box plot 
    df_z.boxplot(by = 'group',  layout=(3,4), figsize=(15, 10))

Compare K-means clusters with Hierarchical clusters¶

# K-means converged very quickly with less computation and more optimized algorithm. Hierarchical clustering put
# more stress on the CPU and converged slower than K-means

# K-means have elbow method that gives hint on the number of clusters. If we mix the elbow diagram with the silhoutte
# score in K-means we got the 'K' value right. In hiwrarchical clustering, we had 'dendogram' tree, but it was not
# very intuitive to guess the number of clusters

# K-means was providing good number of customers even with 4,5 and 6 clusters. Therefore, we had to analyze more with
# the box-plots to find any overlaps. With hierarchical clustering, linkages with cophenetic score was bang-on to give
# right number of clusters, even with 4, 5 or 6 clusters, the linkages with high cophenetic score gave only 3 clusters

# With K-means, the algorithm runs and provides all the results to look, but with the hierarchical cluster, we need
# to look at the dendogram diagram and then further work on the model to manually provide the dendogram score to cut
# the dendogram tree at the right place to get the right number of clusters. The manual work in K-means is to guess
# the 'k' value but we have helper diagrams like elbow and silhoutte to guess the 'k' right, specially when both
# diagrams are used together

# As for finding the number of cluster, both K-means and hierarchical did good job in finding the number of cluster
# that are fairly non-overlapped

# Hierarchical clustering with dendogram clearly explains how the clustering was formed, it is a white box report
# that can be easily related to the final clustering results. However, K-means is a black box method and is highly
# dependent on the initial chosen centroids and may not provide the same results. 



    


















k-means Clustering
Hierarchical Clustering






k-means, using a pre-specified  number of clusters, the method  assigns records to each cluster to  find the mutually exclusive cluster  of spherical shape based on distance
Hierarchical methods can be  either divisive or agglomerative.




K Means clustering needed advance knowledge of K i.e. no. of clusters one want to divide your data.
In hierarchical clustering  one can stop at any number of clusters, one find appropriate by interpreting  the dendrogram.




One can use median or mean as a cluster centre to represent each cluster.
Agglomerative methods  begin with ‘n’ clusters and  sequentially combine similar clusters until only one cluster is obtained.




Methods used are normally less computationally intensive and are suited with very large datasets.
Divisive methods work in the opposite direction, beginning with one cluster that includes all the records and Hierarchical methods are  especially useful when the target is to arrange the clusters  into a natural hierarchy.




In K Means clustering, since one  start with random choice of  clusters, the results produced by running the algorithm many times may differ.
In Hierarchical Clustering, results are reproducible in Hierarchical clustering




K- means clustering a simply a division of the set of data  objects into non- overlapping subsets (clusters) such that each  data object is in exactly one subset).
A hierarchical clustering is a set of nested clusters that are arranged as a tree.




K Means clustering is found to work well when the structure of the clusters is hyper spherical (like circle in 2D,  sphere in 3D).
Hierarchical clustering don’t work  as well as, k means when the  shape of the clusters is hyper  spherical.

# Elbow diagram and silhoutte gave hint that 3 might be a good number of clusters. But, the elbow diagram also hinted
# that it was still converging at 3. So, I also pick 4 and 5 cluster to run the model for analysis.

# With 4 and 5 clusters, K-means provided a good number of customers per group but most of the group per features had
# overlapping results. Some of the feature had 3 overlapping groups and therefore 4 and 5 was not a good choice for
# the number of clusters. We got some grouping with 4 but again, it was highly overlapped and the box plots did not
# explained a good seperation between these customers.

# So, we picked 3 clusters and the groups formed had the following characteristics:

# Observation with 3 segments/clusters with K-Means

# Customers that are extensive users of credit cards with high credit scores
# Segments of customers with highest Average Credit Limit, have more credit cards and visit online more than 
# customers from other group. These kind of customers are lowest in count i.e. 50. Almost all good clusters 
# provided this number. These customers also makes less phone calls and less bank visits but prefer making 
# online transactions and visits. Bank would like these kind of customers since they use more credit cards, incur
# less cost since they use the online banking. They also make less phone calls and less ank visits and therefore
# low maintenance customers.

# Customers with mid range customer count (222). These are customers that have low average credit limit, 
# less credit cards, makes less bank visits, average online visits and had to be made more phone calls. Banks can 
# target these customer to get to use more online feature to reduce the cost involved in phone calls and customer 
# service. Bank can spend more time explaining the benefits of using the credit card over the phone since these 
# customers make more phone calls and have less number of credit cards.

# Customers with most customer count (377). These are customers with average credit limit, good number of credit 
# cards, make more bank visits than other groups but group 2 and low online 
# visits and less number of calls made. These are the most commonly found customers and prefer making transactions 
# physically, instead of phone calls or online visits. Since they are already have a good credit limit and number 
# of credit card, it will involve less time and money to sell new credit cards. These customer can also be encouraged
# and educated to use online banking to avoid more bank visits and thereby reduce the cost incurred in maintaining
# bank locations

# Hierarchical clustering with linkage having high cophenet score ('Average', 'Centroid', 'Complete', 'Weighted', 
# Medium') provided 3 clusters all the way. Even when we created 4 or 5 clusters, it gave either 1 or 2 customers 
# in other clusters and most of the customers were in the 3 clusters. Also, the count of customers in these 
# clusters we almost the same for all high scoring cophenet linkages i.e. (50, around 220 and around 380). 
# These number and cluster formation also match with the K-means clustering. The customer distribution is also 
# the same as the K-means clustering and therefore all the above customers category and distribution apply 
# the same for hierarchical clustering as in the K-means.
